{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.07,0.03,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"3743"},{"type":"tags","id":"3746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44219"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of recurrent joint pain. He has a three-month history of morning stiffness, fatigue, and poor appetite. He has juvenile idiopathic arthritis diagnosed two years ago and takes regular naproxen. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired but not acutely unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He has swelling of both knees and ankles. Recent blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 98 g/L (115-145)\u003Cbr/\u003EMean cell volume 82 fL (75-87)\u003Cbr/\u003EWhite cell count 11.2 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5)\u003Cbr/\u003EPlatelet count 450 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr/\u003EC-reactive protein 45 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003Cbr/\u003EFerritin 180 \u00b5g/L (15-80)\u003Cbr/\u003ETransferrin saturation 15% (20-50)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron deficiency","Secondary to naproxen","Thalassemia trait","Blood loss","Chronic disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with normocytic anaemia in the context of active juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA). The combination of elevated inflammatory markers, high-normal ferritin despite low transferrin saturation, and an underlying chronic inflammatory condition strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic disease\u003C/strong\u003E as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with low ferritin levels, whereas this patient\u0027s ferritin is elevated, likely as an acute phase reactant. While the transferrin saturation is low, this can occur in both iron deficiency and anaemia of chronic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs like \u003Cstrong\u003Enaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E can cause anaemia through gastric irritation and blood loss, or rarely through bone marrow suppression, this patient\u0027s blood results are more consistent with anaemia of chronic disease. The elevated platelet count and inflammatory markers suggest active inflammation rather than drug-induced bone marrow suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassemia trait\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with microcytic anaemia (low MCV), whereas this patient\u0027s MCV is within normal limits. Additionally, there would be no association with inflammatory markers or joint symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood loss\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the chronic nature of symptoms and the absence of any history suggesting blood loss. The platelet count is elevated rather than low, which would be more consistent with chronic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnaemia of chronic disease occurs due to inflammatory cytokines interfering with iron metabolism and erythropoiesis. The hallmark is normal to elevated ferritin with low transferrin saturation, reflecting impaired iron utilisation rather than iron deficiency. Treatment primarily involves managing the underlying inflammatory condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anaemia of chronic disease is characterised by elevated ferritin and low transferrin saturation due to inflammatory cytokines affecting iron metabolism","Active juvenile idiopathic arthritis typically presents with elevated inflammatory markers, morning stiffness, and joint swelling","Iron studies help differentiate between iron deficiency anaemia and anaemia of chronic disease, with ferritin being a key distinguishing feature"],"references":["Equitz E, Powers JM, Kirk S. Etiologies and Outcomes of Normocytic Anemia in Children. J Pediatr. 2024 Aug;271:114041. doi: 10.1016/j.jpeds.2024.114041. Epub 2024 Mar 28. PMID: 38554748.","Gallagher PG. Anemia in the pediatric patient. Blood. 2022 Aug 11;140(6):571-593. doi: 10.1182/blood.2020006479. PMID: 35213686; PMCID: PMC9373018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43593"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T14:07:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T14:08:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading